From having compared the original and translation of a few passages and parts of poems man)r years ago, the impression that remains upon my mind is, that the liberty taken was no more than I thought allowable3 and I am persuaded, that it would have appeared to be still less if I · 'had the translator's own edition. ἢ ln what I have said, I wish to be understood as speak- ing only of the first volume published by Mr Macpherson, of which a number of the poems, episodes, and incidents were known to me in the original: and as some of these were among the most beautiful in the collection, I can easi- ly give the poet credit for other passages of less note con- nectcd with them, which-I may not have heard. The se- cond volume may possibly be equally authentic with the first; but I do not feel myself authorized to speak of it . in the same ternis, as I do not remember to have heard any of it in the original, except what relates to the death of Oscar. l thought, too, when I read it, which was along time ago, that the stile of some parts of it was more curt, abrupt, and affected, than the rest of the poetry of Ossian. l should therefore suspect, that if the translator used too much liberty in any part of his work, it was in this; in which he seems at least to have condemned and fettered the sense, more than perhaps the genius of the original would well bear. 1 do not recolleet whether this observation may be justified by the specimen of the original which I had seen, published with the first editi0n3 but I recollect, that upon comparing that specimen with the translation, l observed several words of which (as I thought) the able · translator inadvertently mis-took tho meaning, which could not well be supposed to have been the case, if, as some al- ledged, any par-t of it was of his own composition.
